post_text: Tripp-Delmont School has been approved to offer feeding through the Summer Seamless Option Program, which will result in free meals offered for all children enrolled through age 18. post_text:
CHANGE TO THE FOOTBALL SCHEDULE:
Sunshine Bible will not be having a football team this fall. We will be playing Northwestern in Tripp on October 2nd instead, which will now be our Homecoming week. We will no longer have a game on September 11th, and will no longer have Homecoming that week. Coronation will now be Monday, September 28th at 7:00pm. The Homecoming parade will be Friday, October 2nd at 1:00pm.

Additionally, Tutor day will also switch to accommodate. Oct. 2nd will no longer be a Tutor Day. September 11th will be the new date for Tutor Day.

If anyone on the Tripp-Delmont side is interested in Cheer Coaching also, please stop in for an application and contact Mrs. Bigge or Mrs. Powell at 935-6766.

2020-2021 VB and FB practice schedules

REMINDER: All 7-12th graders playing athletics need a physical before they begin practices. Physical forms can be found on our website or please stop into the school and we can provide you one üòâ

Change of Plans #342 (hahahaha)

We will continue our flexible learning through the original school calendar with May 15th being our last school day.

Friday, May 8th will be homework pick up and there will be NO MORE work distributed :)

The following week (May 11-15) will be considered a "make-up" week for students who are still missing work. All work will NEED to be collected Friday, May 15th during meal drop off.

Grades will be updated and posted Wednesday, May 20th in order for final report cards to be mailed home at the end of the week.

For the 4th quarter, the Elementary ONLY is moving to a pass-fail grade system. If students continue to complete and turn in work, along with attending their zoom meetings they will pass.

Middle School and High School students will still have their regular percentage grades as this time still counts towards their requirements.

And as always, Thank you for your continued support to our school district. If you have any questions, please don't hesitate to reach out to us.

post_text:
As many of you have already heard, the Governor has asked for schools to stay out of the building for the rest of the school year. We will continue our flexible learning through the original school calendar with May 15th being our last day.

For the 4th quarter, the Elementary is moving to a pass-fail grade system. If students continue to complete and turn in work, along with attending their zoom meetings they will pass. Middle School and High School students will still have their regular percentage grades as this time still counts towards their graduation requirements.

We do already have an approved 2020-2021 calendar with an August start date, but are also looking towards a potential approval of a post-Labor Day calendar if should we need it as a "worst case scenario".

And as always, Thank you for your continued support to our school district. If you have any questions, please don't hesitate to reach out to us.

post_text: We are still in a state of "none community outbreak" - we are NOT seeing a wide-spread increase in Coronavirus, rather this is an effort to continue to clean and make sure that it does not spread in our state.

post_text: At 11:45 this morning, Governor Noem filed a State of Emergency for the state, recommending all state schools close for the entire next week. The concert scheduled tonight will be rescheduled to a later date. The Wellness Center and Gym will also be shut down during the following week to deep clean. Thank you for your patience during this time. Please continue to wash appropriately and clean high traffic surfaces.

post_text:
CORONAVIRUS INFORMATION.
You will find a letter from the school district coming home with your child(ren) tonight. Please read it. We highlight both what the school is doing to take precautionary steps, but also what you can do to protect yourselves at home. Essentially, the care taken is to wash your hands thoroughly, for 20 second with soap before rinsing, and to wash often. In addition, wipe down any surface areas that have high hand traffic with wipes. The CDC put out that 5Tbsp. of bleach diluted to a gallon of water would work well to spray and let dry. We will also be using our school social media platforms to provide more community health awareness and tips and tricks to staying healthy that the CDC has suggested. Thank you! Andrea

post_text:
As we work to ensure our students and families are safe, we share this comic developed just for kids. At times we may think that their ears are unaware, but they hear our conversations and can become scared. We are sharing this comic that promotes healthy hygiene and provides guidance for what kids can do to help with our staff and students, as well as with our families. Copies will come home with your children so that you too can help provide guidance and calm any fears for your family.

https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/28/809580453/just-for-kids-a-comic-exploring-the-new-coronavirus
